It is unfortunately quite clear that only the likelihood of prosecution is effective in changing behaviour. Not the range of punishment nor appeals to morality or common sense -- just, will I get arrested? Best known example is the reduction of drunk driving when the police make special and widely publicized enforcement efforts. 
Formerly, some jurisdictions raised the fines on drunk drivers. Nada. The fines now stay the same; the difference in criminal behaviour corresponds to the increase in police presence, administration of breathalyzer tests, and arrests.

